Thin CLI layer: parses argv via `clap` into `Cli { path: Option<String>, hook: bool }` and dispatches to `crate::serve`/`crate::hook`, rendering to an injected `Write` rather than `println!` (so `clippy::print_stdout` stays enforced crate-wide). Contains no chain logic itself — it's a router that also decides, in path mode, whether to consult the session ledger.

`dispatch<E: Env, W: Write>(env: &E, base: &Path, cli: Cli, stdin: &str, out: &mut W) -> Result<(), CtxError>` is the single entry point. If `cli.hook` is set, it calls `hook::run(env, base, stdin)` and writes the JSON only if non-empty — hook mode is fail-open, meaning it returns `Ok(())` silently on empty output and never surfaces chain errors, only writer I/O errors. Otherwise it requires `cli.path`, erroring `CtxError::Usage` if absent. In path mode, it checks `env.env_var(session::ENV_SESSION_ID)`: if unset, it calls `serve::chain_for` + `serve::render` (no ledger interaction); if set, it calls `serve::fresh_chain_for(env, session_id, path)`, folding served nodes into the session dedup ledger, and substitutes the constant `NOTHING_NEW` message when everything for that path was already shown this session. This session-var branch is the mechanism that lets a manual CLI invocation and a Claude Code hook invocation share one dedup record — editing the env-var name or the branch condition breaks that sharing.

`Cli::hook_mode(&self) -> bool` is a small `const fn` accessor used by callers to decide whether stdin must be read before calling `dispatch` (hook mode consumes stdin; path mode ignores the `stdin` param entirely).

`out_err` wraps any `std::io::Error` from the output writer as `CtxError::Io { path: "<stdout>", .. }` — the literal path string `"<stdout>"` is a synthetic marker, not a real path, and appears only here. All writer errors in both modes go through this wrapper, so any error path bypassing it would produce an inconsistent `CtxError::Io.path` value.